Rebellious Central Bank Governor?
Prague – Lately, there has been widespread criticism of central banks in advanced economies.
The main points of attack are as follows: monetary policymakers have been too active since 2008, their powers have expanded too rapidly, and this is endangering the economy.
This claim—strangely, it is popular among ideologically opposed camps such as liberals and neo-Marxists—is entirely wrong.
The critics failed to understand that modern central banks are responsible not only for containing inflation but also for maintaining long-term price stability.
The level of prices is akin to a person's body temperature and can fluctuate within a range that is neither too high nor too low without causing severe symptoms.
When combating deflation caused by weak demand and containing inflation driven by excessive demand, the central bank must be equally "proactive."
Despite the battle being entirely symmetrical, public assessment of it is bizarrely skewed, especially in countries where people are very financially conservative.
This includes my home country, the Czech Republic. The Czech savings rate is small, and the loan-to-deposit ratio remains well below 100%.
The Czechs are concerned about inflation, even though the Czech inflation rate reached a 13-year low last year, and the Czech National Bank, of which I have been deputy governor since 2013, has been working to eliminate deflation risks.
Other common complaints about the policies of developed countries' central banks since 2008 is that they have induced redistribution effects.
Of course it will be that way, but so what?
Any monetary policy action redistributes wealth.
Raising interest rates pleases savers, while lowering interest rates benefits borrowers.
Importers prefer strong exchange rates; exporters prefer weak exchange rates.
For monetary policy to be effective, it must have different impacts on different groups at different times.
This is not a mistake; this is the essence of monetary policy.
Some critics also argue that central banks have failed to meet their inflation targets anyway, so their activism is not only unnecessary but also ineffective.
At times, they even place these contradictory criticisms in the same sentence as if they were blaming someone for causing casualties while firing blanks.
The reality is that central banks around the world have succeeded – and succeeded spectacularly – in maintaining price stability and preserving the purchasing power of money during and after the global financial crisis.
Without their intervention, their economy would have faced a catastrophic deflation, a massive downturn in asset prices, and a complete collapse of both the financial and real sectors.
Clearly, strong action was the right approach to addressing the crisis (which does not, of course, address what role the central bank played in the outbreak of the financial crisis).
In a system that uses a elastic currency with no intrinsic value, the money supply must change over time in order to keep its purchasing power roughly constant.
Therefore, price stability, rather than the quantity of money, is the important issue.
The expansion of the central bank's balance sheet reflects the depth of the problems faced by many economies after 2008.
In this context, the central bank took necessary measures to maintain purchasing power and price stability.
For them, there is no such thing as activism; only an eternal duty to be fulfilled.
If you find this assertion to be tinged with arrogance, let me provide some evidence.
People vote with their pocketbooks.
If their currency's purchasing power took a severe hit after 2008, naturally they would seek to convert it into something else (other currencies, precious metals, or other savings vehicles).
This is rarely seen in developed countries.
Of course, many central banks around the world have not achieved their inflation targets.
(The central bank typically defines the ideal economic "temperature" as an annual inflation rate of around 2%. )
) This is undoubtedly unpleasant, but it does not lead to disaster, particularly given that much of the deflation stems from supply – rather than demand – shocks, such as plummeting oil prices.
This shock benefits consumers and poses no threat to price stability, at least for net oil-importing countries.
Consider this scenario.
A company plans to increase its sales revenue by 2%, but the managers achieve this by increasing it by 1% each year for two consecutive years.
Do you think this company will fail?
It probably won't.
After all, private companies' profit and revenue forecasts can easily deviate by 10% or more from actual figures.
The operating environment variables for most businesses are fewer than those of the central bank.
If that's the case, how can you expect the central bank to achieve precise inflation targets regardless of the economic environment?
It must be clarified that I did not say that the central bank should not work hard to approach its targets.
They should certainly be that way.
Moreover, they should certainly not allow inflation expectations to become unstable.
But when it comes to judging central banks, people need to strike the right balance.
They indeed need to stop saying things that are not true - for example, that the central bank's policy arsenal is not only depleted but is also running out.
Monetary policymakers have ample weapons and unlimited ammunition to use at their discretion.
These weapons have different calibers, and their effectiveness varies at different times.
Not all weapons are suitable for all situations in all economies.
But the central bank's theoretical ability to create and destroy money is unlimited.
The central bank governor should say "enough" to the ignorant criticism they face.
None of our critics have been able to explain in a clear and credible way why price stability is not a valid goal, what key objective the central bank should instead pursue, or what fundamentally different approach they believe should have been taken since 2008.
There is a simple reason for this: the approach taken by central banks of advanced countries since the crisis has been the right one.
In fact, this policy pulled our economy back from the brink.
You're welcome.
